</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="48" type="habitat and ecology.">
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="48">Habitat and ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="48">Desert washes, flats, and slopes in coarse, sandy soil.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="48" type="phenology.">
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="48">Phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="48">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Still" authorityYear="2014" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Papaveraceae" genus="Eschscholzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Papaverales" pageId="3" pageNumber="48" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="androuxii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">Eschscholzia androuxii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
typically flowers between late-February and early-May but may flower earlier in the season, including in the fall, during years with a summer rain and cool fall temperatures.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="48" type="etymology.">
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="48">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="48">
The species is named for James 
<normalizedToken originalValue="André">Andre</normalizedToken>
and Tasha La Doux, two desert botanists and friends that helped point to the problems with desert 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Papaveraceae" genus="Eschscholzia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Papaverales" pageId="3" pageNumber="48" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="48">Eschscholzia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
identification.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="48" type="suggested common name.">
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="48">Suggested common name.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="48">Joshua Tree poppy.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="48" type="conservation status.">
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="48">Conservation status.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="3" pageNumber="48">As this is a new taxon it has yet to be considered for conservation status. Due to the limited range and low number of occurrences, the author suggests the California Native Plant Society consider this taxon for listing as a rare plant.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
